&lt;p>First, you will need to create a new repository on GitHub. This repository will be used to store the code for the workshop and will
be the repository which will run all the GitHub Actions and Workflows.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>We are going to make a new repository using the GitHub web interface.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>1 - Steps</title><link>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/2-introduction/1-steps/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/2-introduction/1-steps/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction-to-steps">
 Introduction To Steps
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#introduction-to-steps">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;div class="slide">
 &lt;div class="slide-nav">
 

 

 

 
 &lt;a rel="noopener" class="book-btn nextSegment" style="position: absolute; right:0">
 Next
 &lt;/a>
 

 
 &lt;/br>
 &lt;/div>

 &lt;div class="slide-content">
 &lt;p>Steps are the basic building block for jobs. These are the actual &lt;strong>actions&lt;/strong> part of GitHub Actions.
They are essentially a task that you need done. This could be a task that uses code in the repository, but
it does not have to be. A step could essentially do anything.&lt;/p>
&lt;div style="position: relative;">
 &lt;div>
 &lt;blockquote class="book-hint info">
&lt;p>Think of steps as analogous to &lt;code>functions&lt;/code> in code. They are a logical grouping of behaviors.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>2 - Jobs</title><link>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/2-introduction/2-jobs/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/2-introduction/2-jobs/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction-to-jobs">
 Introduction To Jobs
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#introduction-to-jobs">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;div class="slide">
 &lt;div class="slide-nav">
 

 

 

 

 
 &lt;a href="https://carsonoid.github.io/workshop/2-introduction/3-workflows" class="book-btn" style="position: absolute; right:0">
 Next
 &lt;/a>
 
 &lt;/br>
 &lt;/div>

 &lt;div class="slide-content">
 &lt;p>In GitHub Actions, jobs represent a series of steps that are executed in order. Important things to know about jobs:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Jobs must run on a single &lt;a href="https://docs.github.com/en/actions/writing-workflows/choosing-where-your-workflow-runs/choosing-the-runner-for-a-job">runner&lt;/a>&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Jobs have a &lt;code>workspace&lt;/code> which persists between steps&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Jobs can trigger other jobs&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Jobs &lt;em>must&lt;/em> be defined inside a &lt;a href="https://docs.github.com/en/actions/writing-workflows/about-workflows">workflow&lt;/a>&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;div class="pagebreak">&lt;/div>
 &lt;/div>
&lt;/div></description></item><item><title>3 - First Workflow</title><link>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/3-first-workflow/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/3-first-workflow/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="first-workflow">
 First Workflow
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#first-workflow">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;div class="slide">
 &lt;div class="slide-nav">
 

 

 

 
 &lt;a rel="noopener" class="book-btn nextSegment" style="position: absolute; right:0">
 Next
 &lt;/a>
 

 
 &lt;/br>
 &lt;/div>

 &lt;div class="slide-content">
 &lt;div class="book-columns flex flex-wrap" style="justify-content: center; align-items: center;">
 &lt;div class="flex-even markdown-inner" style="flex-grow: 1; text-align: center;">
&lt;figure>&lt;img src="https://carsonoid.github.io//art/bluegreen-dog-icons/turning.png" width="100%">
&lt;/figure>
 &lt;/div>
 &lt;div class="flex-even markdown-inner" style="flex-grow: 3; text-align: inherit;">
&lt;p>Once you have the bootstrapped repository and workshop content from the &lt;a href="https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/1-create-repo/">Create Repo Page&lt;/a> you are ready
to create your first GitHub Actions Workflow!&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The general overview of this workflow:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Run on push to the repository&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Contains a single job which should
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Clone the repo&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Install &lt;code>hugo&lt;/code>&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Build the site&lt;/li>
&lt;li>(sometimes) Publish the site to GitHub Pages&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;div style="position: relative;">
 &lt;div>
 &lt;blockquote class="book-hint info">
&lt;p>There are many, many more fields that are valid for workflows, jobs, and steps then we will
cover here. &lt;a href="https://docs.github.com/en/actions/writing-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions">See the docs for all the options&lt;/a>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>3 - Workflows</title><link>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/2-introduction/3-workflows/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/2-introduction/3-workflows/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction-to-workflows">
 Introduction To Workflows
 &lt;a class="anchor" href="#introduction-to-workflows">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;div class="slide">
 &lt;div class="slide-nav">
 

 

 

 

 
 &lt;a href="https://carsonoid.github.io/workshop/3-first-workflow" class="book-btn" style="position: absolute; right:0">
 Next
 &lt;/a>
 
 &lt;/br>
 &lt;/div>

 &lt;div class="slide-content">
 &lt;p>In GitHub Actions, workflows are a colleciton of jobs. Important things to know about workflows&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Workflows can define multiple jobs&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Workflows can be called many ways:
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>By code change&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Manually&lt;/li>
&lt;li>By other workflows&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Workflows do not actually execute directly, they only define jobs which get executed&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;div class="pagebreak">&lt;/div>
 &lt;/div>
&lt;/div></description></item><item><title>4 - Actions Deep Dive</title><link>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/4-actions/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://carsonoid.github.io//workshop/4-actions/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="actions">
